Curly braces designate scope in C like languages:<p><pre><code>    int i = 100;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    if (1) {
        int i = 200;
        std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; std::endl;
    }
    std::cout &lt;&lt; i &lt;&lt; std::endl;
</code></pre>
giving<p><pre><code>    100
    200
    100

</code></pre>
They don&#x27;t seem to serve such a purpose in Pytov. Eyeballing the source, it looks like you&#x27;d get this:<p><pre><code>    i = 100
    print (i)
    if (True) {
        i = 200
        print (i)
    }
    print (i)
</code></pre>
giving<p><pre><code>    100
    200
    200
</code></pre>
So what&#x27;s the point?

Python already has support for optional braces.<p><pre><code>  def say_word(word): #{
    print(word)
  #}</code></pre>
